AGI - <a href="https://www.agi.it/estero/news/2024-02-16/navalny-morto-in-carcere-25323769/">One year after the death in prison </a> of the main opponent of the Kremlin >, Alexei Navalny's supporters will today organize commemorations, including a visit to his grave in Moscow, >
&nbsp;
These tributes come at a time when the Russian opposition, beheaded by the loss of its prominent figure and dilated by internal struggles, is in a position of unprecedented weakness. exiled to different countries abroad, its leaders struggle to rekindle the flame of the struggle against Vladimir Putin, > especially in Russia, where every criticism of the government is severely repressed.
&nbsp;
Charismatic anti-corruption activist and political enemy number one of Vladimir Putin, Navalny had been declared "extremist" by the Russian judicial system.> To publicly mention the opponent or organization, the Anticorruption Fund (FBK), without specifying that "extremists" have been declared, exposes offenders to heavy sanctions. This threat remains valid despite his death, which occurred in unclear circumstances in an Arctic prison on 16 February> 2024, and despite exile outside Russia of almost all his collaborators. According to the former right wing of the opposition, Leonid Volkov, "Alexei's supporters will organize commemorative events around the world".
&nbsp;
In some places will be held gatherings or marches, in others will be projected a documentary dedicated to him. The widow of Navalny, Yulia Navalnaya, who took over the reins of his movement, will participate in an event in Berlin, where many supporters of the Russian opposition live.
&nbsp;
"Wherever you are, in Russia or abroad, we strongly hope that on February 16 you will meet people who think like you", wrote Volkov, indicating the opening hours of the Borissovskoye cemetery in Moscow, where Navalny is buried. Telegram pro-Cremlino channels warned the supporters of the late opposition exponent from going to the cemetery. "We give a brief advice to those who intend to go there but are not sure yet: do not go there!" reads in a message shared by Kremlin supporter Dmitry Smirnov and other channels.
&nbsp;
In the message we talk about the "Great Brother and his eye always vigilant", with the photograph of a sign that signals the presence of a surveillance camera at the cemetery gates. Russian authorities have methodically dismantled the movement of Alexei Navalny, sending many of his supporters to prison and the same opponent. > Four journalists are currently under trial in Russia for "participation in an extremist group", accused of producing images for the team of Alexei Navalny. In January, three of the lawyers defending the opposition leader were sentenced to prison sentences ranging from three and a half to five years for sending his messages while in detention.
&nbsp;
<div </div
