AGI - A new unit of espionage > is leading the shadow war of Russia against the West. > According to Western intelligence officials, cited by the Wall Street Journal, Russian intelligence services have a new "hospitable" unit that targets the West through secret attacks across Europe. Known as Department of Special Missions,> the unit is located in the headquarters of the Russian military intelligence - the Gru - a nine-storey tower, known as the aquarium, completely in glass, surrounded on all four sides by a two-storey structure without external windows.
&nbsp;
The department provides for the use of veterans of some of Russia's most daring clandestine operations in recent years and its missions have so far included attempted murder, sabotage and even an attempt to put incendiary devices on aircraft. For service officials "the creation of the department reflects Moscow's attitude in time of war against the West".
&nbsp;
Despite the news being reported today by the U.S. newspaper, the espionage unit was established in 2023> in response to Western support for Ukraine.<br> The Kremlin sees the Western accomplice of Ukraine in attacks on Russia, such as the sabotage of the North Stream pipelines, the killing of high officials in Moscow and Ukrainian attacks with long-range Western missiles.
&nbsp;
For NATO Deputy Deputy Secretary-General, James Appathurai, "Russia believes that it is in conflict with what it calls 'the collective West' and is acting accordingly, until it threatens us with a nuclear attack and strengthens its army".&nbsp; The Kremlin spokesman Dmitry Peskov said that "this is, as usual, totally unfounded accusations."
&nbsp;
It is believed that the new department, known to intelligence officials with the Russian acronym Ssd, > is behind a series of recent attacks against the West, including the attempted murder of the general manager of a German gun manufacturer and a plot to put incendiary devices on aircraft used by the Dhl shipowning giant. The Ssd would have assumed some powers from the Fsb>, the country's largest intelligence service, and absorbed Unit 29155, which according to Western intelligence services, was behind the poisoning of 2018 of a Russian double-game agent, Sergei Skripal, who took place in the UK.
&nbsp;
Three would be his general tasks: perform murders and sabotage abroad, infiltrate Western companies and universities and recruit foreign agents. > According to Wsj, the department would have tried to recruit agents from Ukraine, developing nations and countries considered 'friends' of Russia, such as Serbia. The department would also run a special elite operating center, known as Senezh, where it is assumed that Russia trains some of its special forces.
&nbsp;
To oversee the operations, would be two men, Colonel General Andrey Vladimirovich Averyanov> and his deputy, Lieutenant General Ivan Sergeevich Kasianenko.> The first is a veteran of Russian Chechen Wars and is sought by the Czech police for its alleged role in an operation of 2014 in which, to blow up a munitions warehouse, two people lost their lives. Following his involvement in the occupation and annexation of Crimea, President Vladimir Putin gave him the highest Russian honor, the Hero Medal of Russia.
&nbsp;
Kasianenko - who according to Western intelligence officials would supervise Wagner's secret operations in Europe after Prigozhin's death - would instead coordinate the operation to poison Skripal and his daughter, Yulia, who survived poisoning but were seriously injured. For this poisoning Russia has always denied any involvement.

